metadata.name: Klyft #691
metadata.description:
“Klyft” is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at PARIS+ par Art Basel.

Klyft is a juxtaposition of two different projections for the future. One, made by the World Economic Forum, suggests that the global gender gap will have closed by the year 2154. The other, by the UN IPCC, estimates that global warming will reach 3.2 degrees celcius by the year 2100.

Klyft makes use of the unique temporal aspect of computational art by developing its expression gradually over the next 132 years. As we come closer to 2154, the space between the two shapes in Klyft will grow smaller to symbolize the closing of the gender gap. As time goes on, however, Klyft also becomes more and more glitched out to represent the projected increases in greenhouse gases and climate catastrophes.

In the end, Klyft’s expression will be heavily corrupted, and the two shapes will have reached each other.

· URL parameters ·

You can add the following parameters to the URL to change the behavior of the piece.

date=<YYYY-MM-DD> — See how Klyft looks on another day. Use the format YYYY-MM-DD. 

color=<number> — See the piece in another color scheme. The numbers loop around, so 17 equals 0, 18 equals 1, etc. 

resolution=<number> — View the piece in a higher resolution. 1 is normal resolution, 2 is double, etc. No decimals allowed.

image=true — Save the piece as an image. 

record=true — Save the piece as a video in WEBM format.

Adding the following URL parameters will show Klyft in double resolution on the day gender equality is achieved according to the WEF:

date=2154-01-01&resolution=2

Adding the following URL parameters will save a video of Klyft in the ‘Stokkendahl Dalgas’ color scheme:

color=14&record=true

· Interactions ·

Pressing the following keys will trigger functionality as well as add related URL parameters automatically. 

Pressing D will increment the date by 1 year.

Pressing C will increment the color index by 1.

Pressing R will toggle between normal and double resolution.

Pressing I will toggle the image URL parameter, which saves the piece as an image. Only works outside of iframe.

Pressing V will toggle the video URL parameter, which saves the piece as a video. Only works outside of iframe.

There are secret key presses as well. Some of them only work outside of iframe. 

· Accessibility ·

Klyft is built to support screen readers. It has been tested using MacOS’ VoiceOver, and uses p5.js’ describeElement() to provide screen reader functionality.

If you have any comments (good or bad) on the screen reader integration, don’t hesitate to reach out on my Twitter: @ada_ada_ada_art. 

· Credits and license ·

Klyft is made with p5.js.

Klyft is licensed under a modified version of the Climate Strike License (CSL).

metadata.name: Rite of Passage #289
metadata.description:
In life, we all take different paths, different rites of passage, and while the end is all that's ever true, we will still all view it and experience it in very different ways, like that masterpiece hanging on the wall at the end of our gallery visit. 
  

There are always things that we will never have the power to change, but at the same time, we determine the route, we influence the journey, we can choose the person we want to be. We'll look back on memories, we'll have regrets, and we'll think about what could have been - but unlike this artwork, in the end we won't be able to change the final output by simply pressing a number - so live well and be happy my friends. 

---------------------

Generative artwork by Sykcolo / @sykcoloart

Primary sale proceeds:
50% to Processing Foundation
50% to Savepakistan

Royalties:
50% to the original minter
50% to artist (me)

Press '2' to '4' to see what could have been + increase pixel density. 
Press 's' to save

Details:

150 hand-picked colour pallets (thanks to @SteveMakerspace for colour selection method)
2 Frame types
4 Art types
2 Times of day (light or dark background)

License: MIT

Happy Birthday fxhash

metadata.name: RushGushBlush #339
metadata.description:
Let's celebrate #fxhashturnsone with a cascade of colors!

This is just my second release on fxhash and I couldn't be happier to dedicate this project, however simple, to this amazing community.

I could go on describing the details of this piece but honestly I just wanted to create something very colorful for the party, without putting too many hidden meanings! :)
(Or maybe not...)

Happy birthday fxhash!

---

80% of primary sales will be donated to the Processing Foundation and Save Pakistan.

---

There are 17 different palettes and 3 formats, hope you'll find a combination that makes you happy!
The texture might look weird in thumbnails, so I recommend opening the piece in full screen and/or download the png by pressing "s".

---

By Todemashi 2022
NFT License 2.0

### NOTES
Made with p5js.
This project uses fx(stdio) by @alt_escapism - https://altesc.art/stdio

metadata.name: Express Yourself #127
metadata.description:
A unique collaboration with YOU the collector.

Using fx(params) allows you to create and sign your minted artwork, expressing yourself with words, colour and graphics.

Make Your Mark.
Stand For Something.
Value Kindness Every Day.

The minter will receive 40% of secondary sales.
10% to girls who code.

Typography is a fine art, and browsers can be fickle, so there are params to allow you to fine-tune and layout your text, your way.
The preview will differ from the final minted work, the text and colours will remain the same – but the background graphics will randomise on minting, you can see what changes by selecting a new seed.

Some params will overwrite others.

Download in live mode...
S to download in standard resolution 1000x1000
H to download 4000x4000
U to download 8000x8000

metadata.name: Type-o-Graphic #77
metadata.description:
Type-o-Graphic embraces the ethos of David Carson's groundbreaking graphic design work. It explores the intersections of typography, design, art and chance, harnessing the power of randomness to create a series of posters that are a frenetic celebration of typographic chaos.

This collection is intended to be customized and printed. Your initial thumbnail output is only the beginning — several parameters are changeable to find a combination and format to your liking. Please use the keys below to explore the thousands of possible variations within each piece.

Features:
B - Toggle border
N - Change border colour
K - Change background colour (if visible)
T - Toggle top finish (if applicable)
Up/Down - Change colour palette (43)
Left/Right - Change blend modes (20)
L - Change to Landscape
P - Change to Portrait
S - Save image

0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 - Change resolution of image
0 - 600 x 900 - (low-res)
1 - 1200 x 1800 - 4x6" @ 300dpi - (default)
2 - 2400 x 3600 - 8x12" @ 300dpi
3 - 3600 x 5400 – 12x18" @ 300dpi
4 - 4800 x 7200 - 16x24" @ 300dpi
5 - 7200 x 10800 - 24x36" @ 300dpi

See accompanying article for more info:
https://www.fxhash.xyz/article/type-o-graphic

Created with p5js by fauxjebus in 2023
Follow me on twitter or instagram @fauxjebus

metadata.name: Dream Recalls #9
metadata.description:
Based on 24 photographs taken with a kaleidoscope lens.
4 layers randomly blended & (sometimes) stretched to create new arrangements that seem like vague memories of a dream.

Altough the artwork is based on photographs, the algorithm allows for a high number of different outputs.
No traits.

Press "s" in live view to save your Dream Recall.

Photographs, process and code by k4leido_k1d
Twitter: @k4leido_k1d

metadata.name: Murmuration #27
metadata.description: A "murmuration" describes both a swarm of starlings, as well as a low continuous sound. This piece reflects on both phenomena, and uses sound waves as the point of origin for the visual interpretation. The non-repetitive nature of the overlapping oscillations form the basis of a potentially endless experience. Four pre-synthesized waveforms spread across the soundstage have been arranged to highlight the emotional quality of the selected mode. Developed as part of the Forefront Web3 Creator Residency

metadata.name: Wonderscapes #138
metadata.description:
In the infinite abyss of wondering there are some random moments of beauty which will stay in memory and at the end they will remind us that exploration and efforts were not in vain.

This artwork is rendered in real-time using custom webStyleGAN model (~25mb) which was trained on a dataset of about 5000 wonderscapes generated by DALL-E from OpenAI.

In addition to the main generative model, there is a CNN classifier model that filters the rendered images by predicting similarity to landscapes (this may take some time with each generation).

On top of the image generated by the neural network, there is a processing script that converts the value of each pixel into a colored ASCII character, the final result is a 64x64 vector grid with 4096 text symbols.

Controls:
- Press [s] to save the high resolution image

metadata.name: Monsoon #52
metadata.description:
Optimization. It's something that haunts all programmers. Including me. But no longer! Monsoon is a study into the optimization of particle systems for the web. Looking especially deep into dynamic grids and dynamic frame rates.

As for the piece itself, it's a reference to how busy this modern world is. How we're all constantly on the go, whether that is physically, or mentally. Almost feeling like a monsoon. A storm of information. A storm of life. A storm of work. A storm of thoughts. A storm of emotions. A storm of everything. And it's all so fast.

As are the particles. They're all moving around these cyclones of information. Glowing up like neon signs in a busy city. Moving so fast it's almost a blur. Forming into something greater than the sum of its parts.
